&lt;/div>&lt;ul>
&lt;li>&lt;strong>Don&amp;rsquo;t Change Refs During Rendering&lt;/strong> - Never modify ref values in the main component body - only in event handlers or effects.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;strong>Screen Updates Need State&lt;/strong> - Changing a ref value won&amp;rsquo;t update your UI. To show a ref value, sync it to a state value.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;strong>Safety Check First&lt;/strong> - Always check that your ref exists before using it: &lt;code>if (myRef.current) { /* now it's safe */ }&lt;/code>&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;br>
&lt;h2 id="wrap-up">Wrap-Up
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>The useRef hook gives you a direct line to DOM elements and a place to store values that persist between renders without causing unnecessary updates. It&amp;rsquo;s like having a secret toolbox that works alongside React&amp;rsquo;s main system.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Key takeaways:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>Use useState for anything visible on screen&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Use useRef for behind-the-scenes tracking&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Only change ref values in event handlers or effects&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Always check that ref elements exist before using them&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
